05531nam a22009135i 9780812290127DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013962913  a97808122901277 a10.9783/97808122901272doi  a(DE-B1597)450990  a(OCoLC)979685056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0400302bisacsh1 aBaumgarten, Elisheva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPracticing Piety in Medieval Ashkenaz :bMen, Women, and Everyday Religious Observance /cElisheva Baumgarten. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b17 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Standing Before God: Purity and Impurity in the Synagogue -- tChapter 2. Jewish Fasting and Atonement in a Christian Context -- tChapter 3. Communal Charity: Evidence from Medieval Nürnberg -- tChapter 4. Positive Time-Bound Commandments: Class, Gender, and Transformation -- tChapter 5. Conspicuous in the City: Medieval Jews in Urban Centers -- tChapter 6. Feigning Piety: Tracing Two Tales of Pious Pretenders -- tChapter 7. Practicing Piety: Social and Comparative Perspectives -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the urban communities of medieval Germany and northern France, the beliefs, observances, and practices of Jews allowed them to create and define their communities on their own terms as well as in relation to the surrounding Christian society. Although medieval Jewish texts were written by a learned elite, the laity also observed many religious rituals as part of their everyday life. In Practicing Piety in Medieval Ashkenaz, Elisheva Baumgarten asks how Jews, especially those who were not learned, expressed their belonging to a minority community and how their convictions and deeds were made apparent to both their Jewish peers and the Christian majority.Practicing Piety in Medieval Ashkenaz provides a social history of religious practice in context, particularly with regard to the ways Jews and Christians, separately and jointly, treated their male and female members. Medieval Jews often shared practices and beliefs with their Christian neighbors, and numerous notions and norms were appropriated by one community from the other. By depicting a dynamic interfaith landscape and a diverse representation of believers, Baumgarten offers a fresh assessment of Jewish practice and the shared elements that composed the piety of Jews in relation to their Christian neighbors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAshkenazimxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aAshkenazimxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristianity and other religionsvJudaismxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aHasidism, Medieval. 0aJewish way of lifexHistoryvTo 1500. 0aJewish way of lifexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJewsvEuropevSocial life and customsvTo 1500. 0aJewsvFrancevSocial life and customsxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aJewsvGermanyvSocial life and customsxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aJewsvSocial life and customs. 0aJudaismvEuropexHistoryvTo 1500. 0aJudaismvRelationsvChristianityxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aJudaismzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aJewish Studies.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Religion, Judaism 2014z9783110370409oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is 